What I'm trying to say basically is it's cool that they didn't seem to turn anyone away due to capacity. I heard from (I think) locals that Trans Pecos serves food during the day time and it appears they serve higher end coffee as well which would've been nice to have. All in all I would definitely go see another show there.

Great concept, good intentions, but execution could be better.  This is a spot located in East  Bushwick/ South Ridgewood, offering a full cafe during the day, and a live DIY venue at night and on weekends. The guys running the place try their best to offer healthy food options (sandwiches, pastries, coffee...etc) using the best ingredients, and the music curated is eclectic to say the least.  However, I have the following remarks:  + Food prices could be better. Business owners and real estate developers still think that Bushwick is the new Williamsburg, and that the swaths of young artists and professionals moving into the neighborhood every year have a lot of money to spend. They don't. There is no money. $9 for a sandwich the size of my fist is not gonna cut it, especially  in this part of town.  + Given the wide range of music genres playing at the live shows, I suggest (1) they should make it a habit to categorize the music (alt. rock, avant-garde jazz, hip-hop...) so people know what they're getting into (2) lower or even drop the cover charge to encourage people to attend the shows, and instead make money selling drinks and snacks. Keep it simple, keep it cheap. Sorry but I'm not gonna pay $15 so a bedroom artist could live her dream on the stage.  + There is a room downstairs that is often turned into a DJ booth and dance floor. The problem is the only way in or out of it is through a narrow staircase, and that is a hazard. NYC Department of Buildings requires that any basement have at least two exits in case of emergency (smoke, fire, stampede...) and unless they have another Exit hidden somewhere, I only see the one staircase.  TL;DR the current DIY model is leaving many potential customers at home, doing it themselves.
